{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"9c5f06b2-8da2-43ba-a526-e17acc9c65d2","content":"Your project isn't at that path in this workspace, but here's how to configure it.\n\nCreate **`.vscode/mcp.json`** in your workspace root:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"],\n      \"env\": {}\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- **`type: \"stdio\"`** — Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout.\n- **`command` / `args`** — runs `dotnet run --project <path>` to start your server.\n- Make sure your server uses **stdio transport** (not HTTP/SSE). If using the `ModelContextProtocol` NuGet package, that's typically `builder.Services.AddMcpServer().WithStdioTransport()`.\n- If your server needs environment variables (e.g., API keys), add them to `\"env\"`.\n- After saving, open the **Command Palette** → **MCP: List Servers** to verify it's detected.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"26d6ffc1-5eab-4136-bf6a-4c97dfe8f31d","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The project doesn't exist yet at that path. But the user said they built it - they're just asking how to configure mcp.json. I should give them the configuration guidance.\n\nFor VS Code agent mode, the `mcp.json` file goes in `.vscode/mcp.json` in the workspace. For a C# MCP server using stdio transport, the configuration would use `dotnet run` to start the server.","outputTokens":397,"requestId":"B02E:3AF8EE:D4BD53:F16587:6A027CCB"},"id":"b8525dbf-79ce-4d7f-8d2a-3dc30c58162e","timestamp":"2026-05-12T01:07:18.284Z","parentId":"cd82d612-5c45-4957-bdf2-f58602516bb6"}
